	<p>
		Sensorineural hearing loss (SNHL) occurs when the delicate structures of
		the inner ear or the auditory nerve are damaged. This is the most common
		type of permanent hearing loss and can make it harder to hear softer
		sounds, while louder sounds may seem muffled, unclear, or distorted.
	</p>
	<p>
		Inside the inner ear are thousands of tiny hair cells that help transmit
		sound signals to the brain. When these cells are damaged, they cannot
		regenerate, which is why SNHL is typically permanent.
	</p>
	<p>
		At Commonwealth Audiology, our experienced audiologist, Dr. Tiffany Brewer,
